The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, Nov. 7: Indian firms are staring at a severe crunch in quality manpower as the next generation of arts, commerce and science undergraduates are not up to the mark, a Ficci survey said. The new undergraduates fall short of the expectations of the employers with regard to self-motivation, self-discipline, empathy for other workers and management, willingness to learn, good written communication and basic computer skills, the survey said.                             
	 New Delhi, Nov. 7: The power ministry is mulling another big ticket follow-on offer of Power Finance Corporation (PFC) to raise around Rs 6,300 crore by this fiscal-end, even though the finance ministry has retained divestment target at Rs 40,000 crore. It is being discussed, power secretary P. Uma Shankar said.                             
	 New Delhi, Nov. 7: Developing economies such as India and Saudi Arabia have emerged as the most attractive destinations for foreign direct investment after the global economic meltdown, industry body Assocham has said.                             
	 Madurai, Nov. 7: Madras High Court has ruled that the Employees Provident Fund Organisation cannot claim damages from employers for delayed payment of their contribution if there is no intention to commit a prohibited act or actus reus behind the delay.                            
	 New Delhi, Nov. 7: Aviva Life Insurance today announced a capital infusion of Rs 116 crore for business expansion. With this investment, the total paid-up capital of the insurance firm has crossed Rs 2,000 crore to Rs 2,004 crore.                            
	 New Delhi, Nov. 7: State finance ministers have asked the Centre to exclude coal from the list of proposed goods and services tax so that the tax rate does not increase for such an important fuel.                            
	 New Delhi, Nov. 7: Market regulator Sebi wants fund houses to invest part of their profit on cementing ties with investors and curtail commissions and freebies to agents.                                                                                                                          
